transcription.text:
Speaker 1: Thank you for calling Viagra. How can I help you?

Speaker 2: Hi, I'm trying to place an order. I don't know if it went through or not.

Speaker 1: Okay, I can help you out. Can you just confirm your date of birth?

Speaker 2: 3 8 59.

Speaker 1: Thank you so much. I do see your order here.

Speaker 2: Okay, and you live in one of the states. There's like a handful of states, like five states, that your state—

Speaker 1: Law with a telehealth medicine. It's just the doctor has to verify your identity.

Speaker 2: So they sent you a text message with a link and you just have to click that video link and just say your name—

Speaker 1: and date of birth—

Speaker 2: so the doctor can verify your identity. And once you do that—

Speaker 1: He can go ahead and approve your prescription.

Speaker 2: And if you want me to have, or I can have the doctor give you a call if you prefer that.

Speaker 1: How long will that take? Can it go right through?

Speaker 2: The video will be quick, but the doctor, they say, you know, it might take up to 24 hours, 12 to 24 hours—

Speaker 1: for them to call you.

Speaker 2: You want to try the video first?

Speaker 1: Yes.

Speaker 2: Okay, so can I—can I just go back to that?

Speaker 1: Yeah, do you want me to have them resend you the email link?

Speaker 2: Well, I don't know. I might be able to just go back to it. I—

Speaker 1: Can try, and if it doesn't work, I can recall you.

Speaker 2: Yeah, that's perfect.

Speaker 1: Okay. Thank you.

Speaker 2: All right. No problem. Bye. Bye.
